ANALYSIS\":\"Variance analysis\" is a detailed and quantitative investigation into why actual profits differ from the budget, comparing actual costs against standards. This process involves calculating and interpreting variances to understand the nature and magnitude of these differences. By comparing actual financial performance with budgeted or standard performance, variance analysis helps in identifying and explaining variances. This analysis is crucial for maintaining control over a business, improving operational performance, and aiding in performance evaluation and decision-making.", "\"STANDARD COST CARD\":\"An example of a standard cost card for Product XYZ includes sales price, production costs (materials, labor, variable overhead, fixed overhead), standard cost of production, and standard profit per unit.\"", "\"QUANTITY STANDARDS\":\"Quantity standards specify how much resource (raw materials, labor) should be input to produce a unit of product/service.\"", "\"PRICE STANDARDS\":\"Price (or cost) standards stipulate how much should be paid for each unit of resource.\"", "\"VARIANCE INVESTIGATION\":\"The main purpose of variance investigation is to improve operational performance by comparing actual cost and performance with the standard cost of actual performance, understanding the nature and magnitude of variances, and taking corrective actions.\"", "\"USES OF STANDARD COSTING SYSTEMS\":\"Standard costing systems assist in planning, establishing budgets, controlling costs, directing and motivating employees, measuring efficiencies, highlighting opportunities for cost reductions, simplifying the costing of products, and providing a cost basis for tendering contracts or setting sales prices.\"", "\"EXAMPLES OF USE OF STANDARD COSTING SYSTEMS\":\"Examples include manufacturing companies using standard cost cards, service centers setting standard labor times and parts for car maintenance, restaurant and drink retail outlets having standards for ingredients and service speed, and hotel chains using standards for laundry, housekeeping, and restaurant operations.\"", "\"USE OF STANDARDS IN BUDGETING\":\"Standards in budgeting facilitate control, highlight possibilities for cost reductions, use predetermined costs for the budget period, and provide information for reports comparing actual costs with predetermined costs.\"", "\"BUDGETS\":\"Budgets are statements of expected costs that direct activities to an agreed action plan, highlighting the volume of activity and level of costs to be maintained as desired by management.\"", "\"STANDARDS\":\"Standards\" in performance measurement refer to the principles applied in setting targets for managers, including ownership, achievability, and equity. Additionally, standards specify what costs should be for a level of performance achieved, highlighting the level to which costs should be reduced to increase profit.", "\"SETTING STANDARDS\":\"Setting standards involves the combined expertise of those responsible for procuring resource inputs and overseeing their use. It aims to encourage efficient future operations and eliminate inefficiencies.\"", "\"IDEAL STANDARDS\":\"IDEAL STANDARDS\" refer to benchmarks that can only be attained under perfect operating conditions. These standards do not account for any machine breakdowns, interruptions, or idle time, implying that they represent the highest possible efficiency and performance levels achievable in an ideal scenario.", "\"BASIC STANDARDS\":\"Basic standards are long-run average standards based on historical data, which may be out of date and too easy to achieve in the future.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}